Disappointing. I had no trouble installing, configuring, or pairing with my new Reflect meter. Until I started actually doing blood tests. They didn't show up in the app. Nada. And no clear evidence whether the app is actually communicating with the meter at that time (if I change range settings, the app asks me whether to use the meter setting or app setting, but doesn't say when it got the meter setting). So I entered the data manually. Then I realized that I can only set "before meal." I test twice a day: before breakfast ("fasting" - 80-120) and before dinner (ummm ... "behaving"? - 80-130). I don't want "good" tags if I'm out of range, I don't want "bad" tags if I'm in range. I did another test this morning, and instead of entering the reading manually, I started playing with the phone's bluetooth settings, which show the meter is not connected. I clicked "+" to tell the phone to connect to the meter - it didn't. I disconnected the phone from my fitness band - still didn't. I poked around some more. I looked at the meter. It showed the most recent test result, acquired via bluetooth from the meter. Sigh. So I don't know if I just haven't been waiting long enough, if I need to disconnect my fitness band, or if I need to randomly fool with bluetooth settings. But once I get that working, I still will have the most basic problem that the app won't accurately tell me whether or not I am in my target ranges half the time. So far it seems like all I've gained by upgrading from a OneTouch Ultra is smaller blood drops. Oh - and the meter setting time from the app beats the heck out of the Ultras, where I refused to adjust for daylight savings or correct for time drift because setting the time was such a hassle. (Anyone else remember connecting by serial cable and getting a message that the meter time and computer time didn't agree and you needed to manually reset the time? Sheesh louise - why couldn't they just ask if they should correct the meter to match the computer?) What it all the fancy and elegant super-features of meter and app don't amount to a hill of beans if the app and meter won't: consistently tell me if I am in range. If I need to disconnect the fitness band or fiddle with bluetooth settings every time I want to sync, I'll only be syncing once a week, if that. [Google Pixel 3a, Android 12]

A quick note for those having an issue with syncing: Ensure your bluetooth is turned on the meter and the computer/phone; Ensure that the meter has been added to the maximum of 3 devices in the app; Login to the app while the meter is off; Turn the meter on; If a rotating circle doesn't appear in the upper right corner of the meter display within 10 seconds, swipe the circle in the top middle of the app home display (the rotating circle should appear on the meter; If not, turn the meter off & on

I've used this app for about six months and everything worked OK. Then today it wouldn't sync. I tried turning Bluetooth on/off, rebooting my phone, etc to no avail. Finally I uninstalled /reinstalled the app. I was fearful that my readings would all disappear but they were still there. I just couldn't sync. The problem turned out to be that It kept timing out during the sync because I hadn't synced for a few weeks so there was a lot of data to transfer The solution was to keep pressing the up/down arrows to keep the meter from going into sleep mode. So it works now and I find the information useful for tracking my blood sugar. I'm guessing that this was caused by waiting too long between syncs which caused the meter to time out. Unfortunately there are no error codes telling you what to do. It just says 'Failed to sync' which leaves you trying to sort out the problem.

The app itself, seems to work OK for me, but I just started using it a couple of days ago. We will see what happens soon.   A note to LifeScan Europe:   I have read many complaints about your setup screens and the date function, to which you replied: "We use Android's native date picker, which requires you to select the year first by tapping on the year and scrolling to the correct year before selecting the month and day".   This is not possible. This is not a standard Android date GUI. Yours requires you to scroll through the months backwards to your birthdate. I tried several times to tap anywhere on that screen, and it simply does not respond at all to tap input. Actually, the entire setup process does not respond to tap input. Even the name entry. You tap on "First Name" and enter your name. You tap on "Last Name" and nothing happens. You can't select a different text box.  Your only option is to get the order of operations correct and keep hitting the "Next" button, but the order of operations is messed up; you have to START the process by tapping the "I Agree" box at the bottom BEFORE going to the "First Name" entry and only THEN can you continue on with hitting the "Next" button!  If you screw up ANYWHERE in the process, your only option is to abort the entire process and start over from the very beginning (I felt like I was learning a new video game just to register!). Ultimately, it took between 7 and 9 attempts (from the beginning each time), totalling over 40 minutes, to finally get it registered.  I am a very heavy user of touch-devices, and have registered literally thousands of applications over the years, and I have never seen one that took this long to enter name, birthdate and country of use before, ever.   Had this been an app for any purpose other than my health care management, I would have ditched the app after the second or third attempt at registration. Please standardize your setup screen, and please use more Beta testers on various platforms BEFORE releasing/forcing updates to the general users.  Thank you for your time.  Jeff
